00:27:11.130 --> 00:27:13.540 align:middle line:84%
interesting as a
geologist, what I

00:27:13.540 --> 00:27:18.100 align:middle line:84%
can tell you is that last
cycle, 5,000 years ago, we're

00:27:18.100 --> 00:27:22.000 align:middle line:84%
now finding evidence of advanced
technological civilizations

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:26.290 align:middle line:84%
over three times that age,
back into the last ice age,

00:27:26.290 --> 00:27:27.200 align:middle line:90%
and now before.

00:27:27.200 --> 00:27:28.000 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:31.340 align:middle line:84%
So this is not the first
technological civilization

00:27:31.340 --> 00:27:32.140 align:middle line:90%
that's been here.

00:27:32.140 --> 00:27:34.260 align:middle line:90%
But here's the key.

00:27:34.260 --> 00:27:35.750 align:middle line:84%
All of those ancient
civilizations,

00:27:35.750 --> 00:27:39.420 align:middle line:84%
there's no evidence of
war, no evidence, no walls

00:27:39.420 --> 00:27:42.780 align:middle line:84%
to protect the cities, no
evidence of any weapons,

00:27:42.780 --> 00:27:45.060 align:middle line:84%
no mass graves that you
would expect after war.

00:27:45.060 --> 00:27:47.130 align:middle line:90%
None of that has been found.

00:27:47.130 --> 00:27:51.720 align:middle line:84%
The first large-scale war
was discovered-- the evidence

00:27:51.720 --> 00:27:55.500 align:middle line:84%
of that war was ancient
Sumeria 5,000 years ago, right

00:27:55.500 --> 00:27:57.540 align:middle line:90%
at the beginning of this cycle.

00:27:57.540 --> 00:28:00.330 align:middle line:84%
And what scientists
now believe, and they

00:28:00.330 --> 00:28:03.965 align:middle line:84%
were surprised to see this
new evidence-- only since 2008

00:28:03.965 --> 00:28:05.530 align:middle line:90%
have they discovered this.

00:28:05.530 --> 00:28:09.930 align:middle line:84%
There was a massive climate
shift 5,000 years ago,

00:28:09.930 --> 00:28:12.030 align:middle line:84%
very similar to the one
that we're living now.

00:28:12.030 --> 00:28:19.110 align:middle line:84%
And that was the trigger for the
first great wars in our world

00:28:19.110 --> 00:28:22.080 align:middle line:84%
because people
suddenly were competing

00:28:22.080 --> 00:28:23.860 align:middle line:90%
for these vital resources.

00:28:23.860 --> 00:28:25.520 align:middle line:84%
And what makes this
interesting is now,

00:28:25.520 --> 00:28:28.110 align:middle line:84%
5,000 years later, we're going
through a very similar climate

00:28:28.110 --> 00:28:28.910 align:middle line:90%
shift.

00:28:28.910 --> 00:28:32.740 align:middle line:84%
The question is, will we
follow the path of the past?

00:28:32.740 --> 00:28:33.665 align:middle line:90%
Will we choose war?

00:28:33.665 --> 00:28:35.752 align:middle line:90%


00:28:35.752 --> 00:28:36.710 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: So far, though.

00:28:36.710 --> 00:28:38.540 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Because we are
afraid of the scarcity

00:28:38.540 --> 00:28:39.340 align:middle line:90%
of the resources?

00:28:39.340 --> 00:28:41.410 align:middle line:84%
Or we choose cooperation
and mutual aid.

00:28:41.410 --> 00:28:43.367 align:middle line:84%
And we're making that
choice right now.

00:28:43.367 --> 00:28:45.200 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And we're right
in the middle of it.

00:28:45.200 --> 00:28:45.540 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Well, we are.

00:28:45.540 --> 00:28:46.830 align:middle line:90%
And for me, this is the value.

00:28:46.830 --> 00:28:48.420 align:middle line:84%
People say, this is
the 21st century.

00:28:48.420 --> 00:28:50.940 align:middle line:84%
Why would you look
and spend your time

00:28:50.940 --> 00:28:52.980 align:middle line:84%
exploring these
civilizations of the past?

00:28:52.980 --> 00:28:54.010 align:middle line:90%
And are they old?

00:28:54.010 --> 00:28:55.235 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:28:55.235 --> 00:28:56.035 align:middle line:90%
But we can learn.

00:28:56.035 --> 00:28:56.900 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: They teach us, yes.

00:28:56.900 --> 00:28:58.275 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: We can
learn from them.

00:28:58.275 --> 00:29:00.540 align:middle line:84%
And we can discover what
worked and what didn't.

00:29:00.540 --> 00:29:02.240 align:middle line:84%
And the things that didn't
work, let's stop doing them.

00:29:02.240 --> 00:29:04.281 align:middle line:84%
The things that did work,
let's do a lot of them.

00:29:04.281 --> 00:29:07.080 align:middle line:84%
And community and
cooperation are the keys.

00:29:07.080 --> 00:29:09.600 align:middle line:84%
Community and
cooperation are what

00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:14.520 align:middle line:84%
helped them thrive in the
presence of these great changes

00:29:14.520 --> 00:29:15.320 align:middle line:90%
then.

00:29:15.320 --> 00:29:19.535 align:middle line:84%
And I cannot help but think
that our lives are very similar

00:29:19.535 --> 00:29:22.200 align:middle line:84%
to that now, and that the same
things will benefit us now.

00:29:22.200 --> 00:29:24.665 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We're looking at wars
being fought over oil at same

00:29:24.665 --> 00:29:25.790 align:middle line:90%
time as renewable sources--

00:29:25.790 --> 00:29:26.873 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Oil, water food.

00:29:26.873 --> 00:29:28.720 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Water, of
course, and food.

00:29:28.720 --> 00:29:30.230 align:middle line:84%
And then there's
renewable sources

00:29:30.230 --> 00:29:32.960 align:middle line:84%
that at the exact
same time, they're

00:29:32.960 --> 00:29:36.210 align:middle line:84%
being created so fast
with electric cars

00:29:36.210 --> 00:29:39.760 align:middle line:84%
and solar paneling
and, I mean, the wind,

00:29:39.760 --> 00:29:45.097 align:middle line:84%
all of the energy that's able
to be created is endless.

00:29:45.097 --> 00:29:47.180 align:middle line:84%
And at the same time, these
wars are being fought.

00:29:47.180 --> 00:29:50.350 align:middle line:90%
So how do you live personally?

00:29:50.350 --> 00:29:51.160 align:middle line:90%
How do you live?

00:29:51.160 --> 00:29:53.880 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Oh, you saved the
easy questions for last.

00:29:53.880 --> 00:29:55.310 align:middle line:90%
And can you help me understand.

00:29:55.310 --> 00:29:56.420 align:middle line:84%
When you say how do you
live what do you mean?

00:29:56.420 --> 00:29:58.820 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So I know you're
in Northern New Mexico.

00:29:58.820 --> 00:30:01.490 align:middle line:84%
And do you live in a place
that is-- when you said earlier

00:30:01.490 --> 00:30:05.370 align:middle line:84%
in the interview that we
are one with the Earth

00:30:05.370 --> 00:30:08.800 align:middle line:84%
and that we are in this
oneness and everything that we

00:30:08.800 --> 00:30:11.520 align:middle line:84%
do directly will
impact our future,

00:30:11.520 --> 00:30:13.350 align:middle line:90%
do you live off of the grid?

00:30:13.350 --> 00:30:15.380 align:middle line:84%
Do you live in a way that
is one with the Earth?

00:30:15.380 --> 00:30:17.900 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: To the
best of my ability.

00:30:17.900 --> 00:30:22.052 align:middle line:84%
I found the property
where I am now.

00:30:22.052 --> 00:30:23.510 align:middle line:84%
If you or your
listeners, if you're

00:30:23.510 --> 00:30:26.180 align:middle line:84%
familiar with Rudolf
Steiner, the Steiner

00:30:26.180 --> 00:30:27.260 align:middle line:90%
schools and principle--

00:30:27.260 --> 00:30:28.060 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:30:28.060 --> 00:30:31.560 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: When I left the
corporations in the 90's, I

00:30:31.560 --> 00:30:32.434 align:middle line:90%
found this land.

00:30:32.434 --> 00:30:34.850 align:middle line:84%
And it was one of the first
Steiner schools that was built

00:30:34.850 --> 00:30:36.610 align:middle line:84%
in North America
in the late 1800's.

00:30:36.610 --> 00:30:37.410 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:30:37.410 --> 00:30:38.993 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: And it is
made of the Earth.

00:30:38.993 --> 00:30:42.820 align:middle line:84%
They are Adobe buildings,
12-inch thick Adobe bricks.

00:30:42.820 --> 00:30:46.740 align:middle line:84%
And my home and the
land that I bought

00:30:46.740 --> 00:30:48.780 align:middle line:84%
is an hour from
the nearest town.

00:30:48.780 --> 00:30:51.112 align:middle line:84%
It's about a mile from
the nearest neighbor.

00:30:51.112 --> 00:30:53.266 align:middle line:90%
It is not convenient at all.

00:30:53.266 --> 00:30:54.640 align:middle line:84%
And when I left
the corporations,

00:30:54.640 --> 00:30:55.598 align:middle line:90%
I had to make a choice.

00:30:55.598 --> 00:30:58.950 align:middle line:84%
I said, do I want to wake up
every morning in a place that's

00:30:58.950 --> 00:31:03.040 align:middle line:84%
convenient to my work
and my health care

00:31:03.040 --> 00:31:05.250 align:middle line:84%
and the airport, which
I've done all my life,

00:31:05.250 --> 00:31:07.910 align:middle line:84%
or do I want to wake up
surrounded by beauty?

00:31:07.910 --> 00:31:09.460 align:middle line:90%
And I made the choice of beauty.

00:31:09.460 --> 00:31:13.260 align:middle line:84%
And this was March 17th,
1 o'clock in afternoon,

00:31:13.260 --> 00:31:16.030 align:middle line:84%
1990, when I walked out the
door of the corporation,

00:31:16.030 --> 00:31:17.540 align:middle line:90%
the last one I worked for.

00:31:17.540 --> 00:31:18.950 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Cisco.

00:31:18.950 --> 00:31:21.630 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: And it
was a good choice.

00:31:21.630 --> 00:31:23.240 align:middle line:90%
It's not an easy way of life.

00:31:23.240 --> 00:31:25.080 align:middle line:90%
But it is it's very different.

00:31:25.080 --> 00:31:31.050 align:middle line:84%
And so that has been my
primary home since 1990.

00:31:31.050 --> 00:31:32.900 align:middle line:90%
My mother's health has declined.

00:31:32.900 --> 00:31:36.280 align:middle line:84%
And we've had to move
her to a better facility,

00:31:36.280 --> 00:31:38.080 align:middle line:90%
now in Santa Fe, New Mexico.

00:31:38.080 --> 00:31:39.880 align:middle line:84%
And so we have another
place in Santa Fe

00:31:39.880 --> 00:31:41.340 align:middle line:90%
that does get me closer to her.

00:31:41.340 --> 00:31:44.350 align:middle line:84%
It gets me closer to
the airport because I'm

00:31:44.350 --> 00:31:46.630 align:middle line:90%
flying all the time.

00:31:46.630 --> 00:31:48.480 align:middle line:90%
And we do our very best.

00:31:48.480 --> 00:31:49.770 align:middle line:90%
We grow a lot of our own food.

00:31:49.770 --> 00:31:51.540 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You do.

00:31:51.540 --> 00:31:54.750 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Solar is
a part of our lives.

00:31:54.750 --> 00:31:56.450 align:middle line:90%
We have no public utilities.

00:31:56.450 --> 00:31:59.190 align:middle line:84%
We don't have any public
water public or public sewage

00:31:59.190 --> 00:32:00.210 align:middle line:90%
or anything like that.

00:32:00.210 --> 00:32:03.550 align:middle line:84%
And for some people,
they call it primitive.

00:32:03.550 --> 00:32:05.000 align:middle line:90%
I consider it rustic.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:05.970 align:middle line:90%
But it's not primitive.

00:32:05.970 --> 00:32:07.386 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's
very sustainable.

00:32:07.386 --> 00:32:09.010 align:middle line:90%
And I feel very good.

00:32:09.010 --> 00:32:11.330 align:middle line:84%
And my wife Martha and
I have made the choice

00:32:11.330 --> 00:32:12.180 align:middle line:90%
to live that way.

00:32:12.180 --> 00:32:13.030 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You live
close to the Earth.

00:32:13.030 --> 00:32:14.571 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: She loves
growing the food.

00:32:14.571 --> 00:32:15.810 align:middle line:90%
She came in.

00:32:15.810 --> 00:32:17.990 align:middle line:90%
We had our first snow this week.

00:32:17.990 --> 00:32:19.524 align:middle line:84%
She came in from
one of the gardens.

00:32:19.524 --> 00:32:20.940 align:middle line:84%
And she had in her
hand-- I didn't

00:32:20.940 --> 00:32:22.065 align:middle line:90%
know what she was bringing.

00:32:22.065 --> 00:32:24.572 align:middle line:84%
And broccoli is one of my
favorite foods on the planet.

00:32:24.572 --> 00:32:26.780 align:middle line:84%
And she had this beautiful,
perfect stalk of broccoli

00:32:26.780 --> 00:32:27.740 align:middle line:90%
that survived the blizzard.

00:32:27.740 --> 00:32:28.906 align:middle line:90%
She said, look what we grew.

00:32:28.906 --> 00:32:31.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: [LAUGHS] I know.

00:32:31.140 --> 00:32:32.720 align:middle line:90%
It's so fun.

00:32:32.720 --> 00:32:33.990 align:middle line:90%
You pick your own vegetables.

00:32:33.990 --> 00:32:36.020 align:middle line:90%
And we are getting back to that.

00:32:36.020 --> 00:32:37.710 align:middle line:84%
And this is what
resilience ultimately

00:32:37.710 --> 00:32:41.590 align:middle line:84%
is is how we can be resilient
with our Earth, with ourselves,

00:32:41.590 --> 00:32:44.400 align:middle line:84%
with our work, with every
single thing that we do.

00:32:44.400 --> 00:32:46.910 align:middle line:84%
And it ultimately has to do
with, as your book states,

00:32:46.910 --> 00:32:48.170 align:middle line:90%
the heart.

00:32:48.170 --> 00:32:50.510 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: It begins with
the heart for us personally.

00:32:50.510 --> 00:32:54.320 align:middle line:84%
And when it comes to both
us and community, one

00:32:54.320 --> 00:32:56.660 align:middle line:84%
of the first principles
of resilience-- and I do,

00:32:56.660 --> 00:32:58.350 align:middle line:84%
I talk about it in
the book-- is what's

00:32:58.350 --> 00:33:00.710 align:middle line:84%
called the principle
of spare capacity.

00:33:00.710 --> 00:33:02.870 align:middle line:84%
That is the first
principle of resilience.

00:33:02.870 --> 00:33:06.100 align:middle line:84%
And for us, it means
emotional spare capacity.

00:33:06.100 --> 00:33:07.540 align:middle line:84%
It means physical
spare capacity.

00:33:07.540 --> 00:33:13.000 align:middle line:84%
It means the ability to charge
our emotional batteries,

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:16.830 align:middle line:84%
if you will, to the point
where when life changes occur,

00:33:16.830 --> 00:33:18.830 align:middle line:84%
we're not leveled you
know, the first thing that

00:33:18.830 --> 00:33:20.100 align:middle line:90%
doesn't go our way.

00:33:20.100 --> 00:33:22.060 align:middle line:84%
And there are very
specific techniques

00:33:22.060 --> 00:33:26.740 align:middle line:84%
to do that based in science,
taught by indigenous ancestors.

00:33:26.740 --> 00:33:28.330 align:middle line:10%
The institute of
HeartMath, and I

00:33:28.330 --> 00:33:30.660 align:middle line:10%
think you may have worked
with them on this program

00:33:30.660 --> 00:33:32.750 align:middle line:10%
or maybe you will, in
Northern California

00:33:32.750 --> 00:33:40.570 align:middle line:10%
is pioneering this research
into the power of the heart

00:33:40.570 --> 00:33:42.820 align:middle line:10%
in nontraditional ways,
things that you're not

00:33:42.820 --> 00:33:45.650 align:middle line:10%
going to learn about in the
medical books or the textbooks.

00:33:45.650 --> 00:33:48.025 align:middle line:84%
And they have done amazing
work with resilience research.

00:33:48.025 --> 00:33:50.482 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really, wow, fantastic.

00:33:50.482 --> 00:33:52.065 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: They're
helping communities.

00:33:52.065 --> 00:33:53.580 align:middle line:84%
They are also
helping the military.

00:33:53.580 --> 00:33:56.090 align:middle line:84%
They're helping people
to find that resilience

00:33:56.090 --> 00:33:57.220 align:middle line:90%
before they go into combat.

00:33:57.220 --> 00:34:00.400 align:middle line:84%
And also, coming home to
reintegrate into their homes

00:34:00.400 --> 00:34:03.100 align:middle line:84%
and families and communities is
something that a lot of people

00:34:03.100 --> 00:34:04.410 align:middle line:90%
don't think about.

00:34:04.410 --> 00:34:08.210 align:middle line:84%
But you're in battlefield
conditions one day

00:34:08.210 --> 00:34:09.020 align:middle line:90%
that serve you.

00:34:09.020 --> 00:34:13.679 align:middle line:84%
And then 72 hours later, you're
on a plane back to Chicago.

00:34:13.679 --> 00:34:15.989 align:middle line:84%
And so they're helping
to reintegrate.

00:34:15.989 --> 00:34:17.429 align:middle line:84%
And it's all about
this connection

00:34:17.429 --> 00:34:21.010 align:middle line:84%
between the heart and the
brain and how we consciously

00:34:21.010 --> 00:34:22.560 align:middle line:90%
manage this connection.

00:34:22.560 --> 00:34:25.120 align:middle line:84%
And it is fueled
by our emotions.

00:34:25.120 --> 00:34:26.620 align:middle line:84%
And we have the
ability to determine

00:34:26.620 --> 00:34:28.730 align:middle line:90%
which emotions we're creating.

00:34:28.730 --> 00:34:31.120 align:middle line:84%
And that sends a signal
to our brain that releases

00:34:31.120 --> 00:34:32.350 align:middle line:90%
the chemistry into our body.

00:34:32.350 --> 00:34:35.070 align:middle line:84%
So if we want healthy,
life-affirming chemistry,

00:34:35.070 --> 00:34:38.719 align:middle line:84%
we've got to find the language
between the heart and the brain

00:34:38.719 --> 00:34:39.760 align:middle line:90%
to send that signal.

00:34:39.760 --> 00:34:41.719 align:middle line:84%
And this is what the resilience
training is all about.

00:34:41.719 --> 00:34:43.575 align:middle line:84%
So there are different
kinds of resilience.

00:34:43.575 --> 00:34:45.275 align:middle line:84%
It means different things
to different people.

00:34:45.275 --> 00:34:45.739 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, it does.

00:34:45.739 --> 00:34:46.139 align:middle line:90%
I see.

00:34:46.139 --> 00:34:48.264 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Personal resilience,
community resilience

00:34:48.264 --> 00:34:51.750 align:middle line:84%
is about spare capacity for the
community and what's needed.

00:34:51.750 --> 00:34:53.480 align:middle line:10%
And I think some
people-- I just want

00:34:53.480 --> 00:34:56.195 align:middle line:10%
to say this-- in our community,
our New Thought Community,

00:34:56.195 --> 00:34:57.570 align:middle line:10%
I've had people
say to me, Gregg,

00:34:57.570 --> 00:35:00.190 align:middle line:10%
isn't that fear
based if you have

00:35:00.190 --> 00:35:03.572 align:middle line:10%
some extra food in your shelves
or you've got a back-up power

00:35:03.572 --> 00:35:04.530 align:middle line:10%
or something like that?

00:35:04.530 --> 00:35:07.160 align:middle line:10%
And my answer to that, and
I want to be really clear.

00:35:07.160 --> 00:35:09.600 align:middle line:10%
If we're honest with
ourselves about where

00:35:09.600 --> 00:35:11.540 align:middle line:10%
we are in life right
now, we are living

00:35:11.540 --> 00:35:14.090 align:middle line:10%
a rare and precious
moment of extremes.

00:35:14.090 --> 00:35:18.250 align:middle line:84%
And a hallmark of the extremes
is volatility in the things

00:35:18.250 --> 00:35:20.650 align:middle line:84%
that we've taken for
granted in the past.

00:35:20.650 --> 00:35:22.150 align:middle line:84%
Climate change is
a perfect example.

00:35:22.150 --> 00:35:25.520 align:middle line:84%
All it takes is one
big storm to knock out

00:35:25.520 --> 00:35:28.510 align:middle line:84%
the travel between one
community and the next.

00:35:28.510 --> 00:35:31.210 align:middle line:84%
And all of a sudden, the
grocery shelves are bare.

00:35:31.210 --> 00:35:33.090 align:middle line:84%
And we're seeing this
time and time again.

00:35:33.090 --> 00:35:36.030 align:middle line:84%
So I personally believe
it's a responsible thing

00:35:36.030 --> 00:35:39.380 align:middle line:84%
to do, to be honest, truthful,
and factual with ourselves.

00:35:39.380 --> 00:35:40.547 align:middle line:90%
Not about fear.

00:35:40.547 --> 00:35:41.380 align:middle line:90%
Just be responsible.

00:35:41.380 --> 00:35:42.180 align:middle line:90%
Say you know?

